Keep those axes sharp, my friends.

A beautiful, snowy night. The dogs and I traveled 50 miles and didn’t see a single soul. 🐺❄️🔱

For my friends in the lower 48 who have asked if Alaska ever gets snow days…

…well, we have been getting dumped on lately and Atlas’s school bus could not make it down our road. I got a call from the bus driver who asked if we could meet him at a place that the bus could safely get too, so we jumped on the old Ski-Doo and drove just over a mile to meet the bus. Next time we’re taking a dog team. ❄️🔱
What a day. 🐺🥩☕️

The snows ceased, the skies cleared, and the temperatures dropped. It was a chilly -32°F this morning but the cold didn’t stop today’s adventures. The dogs and I traveled just shy of 40 miles and we saw 3 spruce grouse on our journey. Next time I’ll have to bring the .22. A fresh grouse pot pie for supper sounds just right. 🐺❄️🔱

A DAY IN THE LIFE AT -40°F

1) wake up and feed dogs a breakfast of @teamdog.pet
2) Scoop poop
3)Split a days worth of fire wood
4) Stoke the fire
5) Put harnesses, booties, and puff jackets on the dogs
6) Go on an adventure
7) Post run debrief and beers inside with the pack 🐺❄️🔱 #solidday

HAPPY WINTER SOLSTICE!❄️🌛

Today marks the shortest day of the year. We will receive just 3 hrs and 41 mins of daylight and the temperatures have dropped below -40°. These short winter days can psychologically affect the mind while the extreme cold can physically alter the body. It’s tough business living this far north, but come tomorrow our days will shine a little bit brighter. Keep your heads up my friends for the darkness is now fading. ❄️🔱
#raisedbywolves ❄️🔱
This is how you look after spending the day outside in -42°F. Stay frosty my friends ❄️🔱

I have some pretty awesome dogs.

I’m so grateful for my wife, my kids, my family, and my friends; and all the time we spent together this year. Although 2022 was a bit rough at times, it also gave us a lot to celebrate. Here’s to the memories made in 2022 and to the new ones to come in 2023. Happy New Year Everyone. Cheers! 🥂

Meat snacks for the dogs…a pocket beer for the musher. ❄️🔱

In about 3.5 weeks the FTK Pack will embark on a 300 mile journey. We are signed up for the Yukon Quest 300.

This adventure begins in Fairbanks on Feb 4th and travels the Yukon Quest Trail to Circle before looping back and finishing in Central. This will be done with a 12 dog team.

I have narrowed our team down to 15 puppers:
1. Clyde
2. Bonnie
3. Maverick
4. Goose
5. Buttercup
6. Tommy
7. Animal
8. Johnny
9. Tate
10. Miss Piggy
11. Vixen
12. Dasher
13. Dani Rojas
14. Fozzie Bear
15. Gonzo

These dogs have been a blast to work with this season. 8 of the dogs are complete rookies and it’s been amazing watching them transform from FNGs to full blown mature sled dogs. I couldn’t be more proud of my dogs. It will be tough to narrow the team down to 12. 🐺❄️🔱
Post dinner howls under a dancing aurora. 🐺❄️🔱
Last night was lit.
Cruised the river with the dawgs, ate an Uncrustable, watched OG Lion King. #dadlife

Spending the night under the stars, sleeping in a bed of straw, surrounded by a bunch of dogs is one of my favorite parts of dog mushing.

The stress involved in preparation for a big race or journey makes it easy to lose sight of the big picture. But nights like this are what’s it’s all about. I love my dogs and am grateful to be able to have experiences like this with them.

The last training run prior to the Yukon Quest 300 is in the books! Its been a wild ride leading up to this point. Truck problems and human/dog illnesses slowed training a bit, but once everyone recovered and the truck was fixed, training picked up once again. The FTK Pack was able to get in a great race simulation the week before the race. The dogs have been camping and eating great and I can’t wait to embark on our journey this Saturday!

A big thanks to @mikeritlandco and @teamdog.pet for fueling our dogs this season. And a big thank you to all of our dog sponsors. This wouldn’t be possible with out you and I am very grateful for your support. 🙏🏼

Drop bags are all packed! These bags are loaded with essential gear necessary to get you and your team down the trail. Our bags are filled with @teamdog.pet dog food, a  variety of dog meat snacks (salmon, cod, and beef), dog booties, fuel for the dog food cooker, gloves, socks, and human food. Logistically, running a race takes a lot of planning and prepping but the lions share of the work is now done.

In the passed three days, twelve of my dogs and I traveled 300 miles. We battled lots of over flow, glare ice, the worst wind storm I’ve ever been in, and cold nights on birch creek; but all 12 of my fuzzy companions ran across the finish line with wagging tales, smiling faces, and the desire to keep going. Over the next few days I’ll break down each run of race for you. This is a tale that needs to be told from start to finish.

In the mean time there’s so many people I would like to thank.

First, I would like to thank the Yukon Quest, the checkers, trail breakers, vets, and my fellow mushers for making this event possible.

A BIG thank you to @mritland @mikeritlandco and @teamdog.pet for fueling our team this year. TEAM DOG provided the proper nutrition to get my ENTIRE team to the finish with the energy to keep going.

Thank you to all of our individual dog sponsors. Our dog sponsors help cover costs of dog meat (we buy by the ton), dog booties, harnesses, and vet bills.

Thank you @anitajbaker @emilyjobaker @the48hatre for making the trip all the way from PA. @anitajbaker and @emilyjobaker were handling the kiddos and the dogs that stayed back, while @the48hatre hit the road with Jeri to handle for the race. @anitajbaker also made me her famous “bubby’s meatballs” to eat while out on the trail.

Thank you to my beautiful wife, @mrs_ftk , for all that you do for the dogs and me. You’re the glue that keeps the wheels from falling off.

Thank you to all of you who sent prayers, positive thoughts, and good vibes our way.

And last but not least 🥁🥁🥁 Thank you to Maverick, Bonnie, Tommy, Dasher, Dani, Animal, Tate, Johnny, Fozzie Bear, Gonzo, Goose, and Buttercup. You were such a fun group of dogs to travel with and I am so proud of all of you and what you guys accomplished.

🙏🏼 With out all your support there wouldn’t have been a race for FTK. Thank you all. For the strength of the pack is the wolf, and the strength of the wolf is the pack. 🐺❄️🔱

Thanks to Maverick, Bonnie, Buttercup, Tommy, Dani, Dasher, Animal, Tate, Johnny, Fozzie Bear, Gonzo, and Goose…the FTK Pack is now qualified for next year’s Iditarod!

Over the next few days I’ll be breaking down our race and will take you down the trail checkpoint by checkpoint. So stay tuned for that!

In the meantime, make sure you follow the excitement in this years @theiditarod ! The official start begins today at 2 pm Alaska time. Good luck to all the mushers and their dogs who are about to embark on the 1000 mile journey to Nome! 🐺🐶❄️🍻

RACE START TO TWO RIVERS
 
Bonnie and Buttercup led the team out of the start chute on a beautiful 0°F morning in downtown Fairbanks. The first leg of the race took us down the frozen Chena River. The initial river miles had more overflow (water on top of the ice) than I expected. There was one spot where little Buttercup was almost swimming. Between sections of overflow, spectators and fans lined the trail, many of which handed out food and beverages. During the first 20 miles of the race, I had beers, hot dogs, sloppy joes, and fireball shots given to me. It was a great distraction from the fact that my boots and feet were completely soaked and we still had 90% of the race to go.
 
Once we came off the river, we were on our home trails. A fear going into the race was that the dogs would be tempted to turn onto our outtrail to run back to the comfort of their dog houses. To my surprise, the dogs ran directly past the trail that heads towards our home and instead continued onward into the Two Rivers Checkpoint. I grabbed a bail of straw and all the items I needed from my drop bag- dog food and snacks, booties, extra fuel for the dog food cooker, human food, fresh gloves and neck gator, and batteries before hitting the trail again. We traveled another 10 miles (roughly 1 hour) before stopping to camp…

📸 by @kalynhollphotography

TWO RIVERS - 101…Part 1
 
I pulled the team off of the trail onto a little, frozen lake. I set the hook and immediately laid out straw so the dogs could rest while I prepared their meal. I removed the cooker from my sled and started melting snow to make the dogs a warm meal. While the snow melted and came to a boil, I went through the line of dogs and removed booties, checked paws and did a once-over on each dog. Everyone looked happy and healthy. I then set out dog dishes and dealt out dinner. Each dog gobbled down their beef and Team Dog kibble stew and laid back down to catch a few hours of sleep.  While they rested, I cleaned up all the used booties, dog dishes, and trash from my own snacks and packed it up. I carefully repacked my sled and pulled out a bag of fresh booties. Each dog got new set of running shoes and after 4 hours of rest, we hit the trail heading toward the first big summit, Rosebud.
 
The plan was to travel roughly 40 miles and camp right at the base of Rosebud, then, after a good rest and with a fresh team, we would head up and over the summit. The trail to Rosebud was firm and fast. The dogs ate up the miles, and before I knew it, we were at the base of the mountain. I laid out the straw, removed the dog’s booties and started making the dogs a hot meal. The dogs devoured another meal of kibble and beef soup. The dogs enjoyed another 3 hours of rest before getting bootied up for our big climb.
 
Rosebud is a 3,600 foot mountain with a gradual climb for the first ¾ of the trail, but the last 750 feet feels vertical. The dogs moved rather quickly up the first, gradual climb of Rosebud. Once we hit the steep section, I noticed Bonnie and Buttercup turning their heads to look back at me. I am familiar with this behavior and sensed what was about to happen next. Bonnie and Buttercup made one last look back at me before making a sharp 180-degree turn and attempting to run back down the mountain….
.
📸 by @wmphotographyakdogs

ROSEBUD MOUNTAIN

I had recognized the leaders’ hesitation and was able to respond simultaneously. I immediately stopped pushing the sled up the hill and took off sprinting past the team to catch my leaders. Before Bonnie and Buttercup could pass the swing dogs, I was there to meet them and stopped the team from rerouting back down the mountain and losing all the elevation we had gained.
 
Once I got the team lined back out, I decided to put Tommy and Dani in the lead position to give Bonnie and Buttercup some brain rest. I gave the command to go, “Ready, Lets go!” Slowly, inch by inch, the dogs pulled while I pushed the sled up the precipitous mountain. Together, we made it up and over Rosebud. To be honest, Rosebud kicked my ass more than I thought it would. I made a mental note that next year I will be in much better physical condition and the dogs and I will be doing more hill training.
 
Coming down from Rosebud summit was smooth until the last 5 miles. In these final miles before coming into Checkpoint 101, there were multiple sections of glare ice. Glare ice is more or less exactly what it sounds like.  Blue, shiny ice that is smooth from either wind or a thaw/freeze pattern. It is distressing for the dogs to run across because they are unable to get good traction and it is nearly impossible to stop the sled because the brake and snow hook have nothing to grab onto. At times, the glare ice was mixed with overflow. When the dogs approached these unfavorable sections, they would hesitate and stop mid stride, causing dogs to pile up on one another. The neck lines, tug lines and gangline would then all tangle together as the dogs would try to free themselves from the quite literal “dog pile.” I would then have to untangle the lines one by one, line the dogs back out, and physically guide the leaders get through the ice. Although this was frustrating and tedious, I knew we were approaching the checkpoint and we would soon get a chance to reset before our next big climb, Eagle Summit…

CHECK POINT 101

The next leg of the race starts off with a big climb over Eagle Summit, another 3,600 ft mountain. Eagle Summit is notorious for having extreme weather; gusting winds and white out conditions. The plan was to rest in 101 for 6 hours, which put us in last place by about an hour. While I drank a cup of coffee at the 101 checkpoint, a race official told me a story about several Quest mushers who got stuck in a bad storm on top of Eagle summit. The mushers lost sight of the trail and heavy winds forced them off the side of the mountain, far away from the trail they were supposed to be on.  An Apache helicopter had to use their FLIR system to locate the mushers. Once they were found, their location was relayed to a Black Hawk helicopter that rescued the teams once the storm passed. The mushers and their teams could have perished had it not been for those rescue teams. 
 
The weather was beautiful at 101 while I was camping, so a white out was the last thing on my mind. As my rest was coming to an end, I looked up at the summit, which was visible from my camping spot. I could see a white haze near the top of the mountain but otherwise, there was no wind or active snowfall at 101. I saw a snowmachine coming into the checkpoint from the direction of Eagle Summit. On the machine was a friend of ours, Whitney Mclaren. She saw me putting booties on my dogs.
“You heading up there now?” she asked.
“That the plan.” I responded.
While I couldn’t really see her full face, as she was wearing a frosted neck gator pulled up to her eyes, I could read the concern in her eyes.
“I was just up there and it’s getting pretty bad and only getting worse.”

After hearing the weather report, I knew I needed to leave the checkpoint as soon as I could. I wouldn’t be able to wait out the storm that was rolling in because I was already at the tail end of the race pack. If I didn't keep moving, I would be disqualified for being too far behind. I prepped the dogs and myself and we left the checkpoint with Tommy and Dani in lead position….🌬️💨❄️🌨️
.
📸 by @wmphotographyakdogs

After a few miles of rolling hills, we began our ascent up the mountain. At first the storm wasn’t that bad; my team trotted along unbothered. As we climbed, visibility deteriorated and the wind started to blow. The team continued to march forward. I squinted my eyes and scanned side to side, searching for the next trail marker. I could barely make out my leaders as the team trudged up the mountainside.  As I was trying to get my bearings, a gust of wind pushed a flurry of snow into my team. The greyish, white storm engulfed Tommy and Dani and then Buttercup and Bonnie. I felt a sinking sensation in my guts as the first four dogs completely disappeared into the unknown. Then, suddenly, the team stopped moving....
.
📸 by @wmphotographyakdogs

Happy K9 Veterans Day to Frank and all those wonderful doggos that served our country.
 
Frank was the pupper that started my obsession with dogs and was the catalyst that led me to dog mushing. 🇺🇸🔱🐺 #mansbestfriend

The storm was producing strong headwinds that made it difficult for me to walk. I leaned forward into the gusts, trying to cut through the resistance with my shoulders. I tilted my head up to see all the dogs congealed into a ball. The dogs had congregated into a tight huddle, finding security in being close to one another. As I came closer, I could see 12 snow covered faces looking at me with panic in their eyes.  To be honest, I was a little scared too. Throughout my military career, I logged many hours on mountain tops and have been in plenty of wind storms. Just this past fall while elk hunting in Afganak Island, I was in a wind storm with 45 mph sustained winds. But this was different. This was on a completely new level. 
 
Ultimately, I knew we were screwed if we weren’t on the trail, which had seemingly been erased by the high velocity winds. Locating the trail markers became the priority and turning back was not an option. I was afraid to leave the team behind while searching for the trail markers because of the complete lack of visibility. If I strayed too far away from the team, I may not be able to find them again. I grabbed a leash out of my sled bag and clipped into the front of the gang line. I became the new lead dog. Slowly the dogs and I snaked our way along the mountain side in an “S” pattern, searching desperately for a trail marker. All I could see was gray and I struggled to walk as the wind pushed into my body, the cold and snowflakes striking any area of exposed skin on my face like a sandblaster.
 
Just as I was beginning to doubt that I was on the right trail, low and behold…A trail marker! I walked right up to it and thought, “now what?” Do I keep moving forward in this snake-like pattern until I find another trail marker? I sat down for a second and thought, “I wish Brock was here. I could put him in single lead and he would drag the whole team through this storm.”

I sat there for another minute and considered our situation. I may not have Brock on the team anymore, but I do have some of his pups. In this moment of desperation, I decided to put Brock’s son, Maverick, in lead…
.
📸 by @wmphotographyakdogs

GETTING THROUGH THE STORM

Once Maverick and Buttercup were hooked into the front of the line, I pulled the line tight so all the dogs were lined out. I staggered my way through the wind back to the sled. Although I could only see eight of the dogs, the team appeared to be “lined out.” I pulled the hook and shouted, “Let’s Go!” The team started to slowly move up the side of the mountain. Then I saw a trail marker. Then another, and another. At this point I’m pumped up. I can’t see what’s going on up front but whatever the leaders were doing, it was working.
 
Once we got to the top of the Eagle Summit, visibility improved and I could see my leaders again. What I witnessed was mind blowing. I could see Maverick running with his head down, nose to the trail. He was actively sniffing the ground for signs of other teams; yellow snow, a bootie, a dog turd. This is how we were able to stay on the trail.
 
I kept the dogs moving until we were over the top and down the other side, tucked safely in a stand of trees and out of the wind. I stopped the team and handed out snacks. It was here that I realized everything changed. There was something different about the ENTIRE team. The dogs had a different energy about them. The team that had looked at me with fear in their eyes, not wanting to push through the storm, now had a stoic look. They radiated confidence. Getting through the storm seemed to transform my team.
 
On the remaining trail to Central, there were a few sections of open water and glare ice but the dogs charged straight through it without hesitation.  They traveled faster than all the previous miles of the race and had me on the drag mat the rest of the way to Central. I was glad we made it through that storm, simply for the sake of making it out alive but I am also glad we were faced with that challenge. That experience gave me a chance to prove to my dogs that I wouldn’t ask them to do something that we weren’t capable of doing as a team and they proved to me that they are capable of doing even more than I had originally given them credit for. I could feel our bond had a new strength…
.
📸 by @wmphotographyakdogs

How we do nap time at FTK ❄️🔱🐶
#dadlife #daddydaycare

Central – Circle
 
Once we arrived at the Central checkpoint, I got the dogs a warm meal and bedded down. Once they all were tucked in with their fleece trail blankets, I decided to enjoy some of the local fare at the Skookum Roadhouse. 🍔This is the only restaurant in the small village of Central and the Yukon Quest is one of their biggest events all year. I enjoyed one of their famous Quest Burgers and drank an entire pitcher of water. After nourishing myself, I decided to finally get a little bit of rest. I napped for about 1 and a half hours before repacking my sled and starting to put fresh booties on the dogs.
 
The next section of trail was on the infamous Birch Creek. Birch Creek is  notorious for its long “S” turns as it winds its way along for 75 miles until it reaches Circle, the final checkpoint of the 300 mile race. The plan was to break this run in half with a camp out in the middle. I loaded the sled down with the camping essentials -straw, extra dog food, meat snacks, and an Uncrustable and Bubby’s meatballs for me. As we left Central, the skies grew cloudy and the snow began to fall. I remember thinking, “At least this snow will keep things fairly warm on our journey,” but not long after, the snow stopped and I could feel the temperatures plummeting. The temperature dropped to -30F as we twisted and turned our way down the river. We ran about 40 miles before finding a good spot to camp.
 
Once we stopped, I got the dogs bedded down, then fed. While the dogs were sleeping, I changed out my socks, gloves, neck gaiter, and then repacked the sled. The remaining time was spent doing air squats/ busting out dance moves 🕺🏻to try to stay warm until it was time to bootie the dogs for our run into Circle. Three hours later we were running down the river again.
We started moving just as the sun was rising. I was happy to see the sun. Not because I was hoping it would bring warmth, but because I was struggling to stay awake at this point. As the sun rose higher, we ate up the miles and made it into Circle…
.
📸 by @wmphotographyakdogs

Circle – Central
 
Once we got into Circle there was a team of veterinarians waiting for us. The vets gave every dog a thorough examination. They listened to their hearts, their lungs, checked all shoulders, wrists, triceps, hips, paws, and knees. The vets told me the dogs looked great and looked like “they liked their groceries” meaning that they were maintaining their weight well (THANKS TEAM DOG!). I got the team fed and bedded down, their final big rest before the finish.
 
Since this was the final checkpoint of the race, all mushers were required to take a mandatory 6 hour rest here. Circle is the last village on the road system before encountering the mighty Yukon River. The village goes out of its way to make sure the mushers have a warm place to rest and delicious warm food to fill their bellies. The community fire station becomes the gathering place for the YQ volunteers, vets, handlers, mushers and community members. Even though I was exhausted and all I wanted to do was sleep at this point, I had to take advantage of the cornucopia of crock pots and local made foods including salmon right from the Yukon River. After I ate to my heart’s content, I decided to get some rest before our final leg of the race.
 
 The dogs were fired up after another 6 hours in the straw.  We uneventfully left the Circle checkpoint and flew down Birch Creek. One of the reasons the dogs may have been moving so fast is because it was cold on Birch Creek, -35 degrees cold, and the dogs always seem to move better in the cold. We were averaging 10 MPH 45 miles into the run.
 
With only 30 miles to go I decided to camp despite the dogs wanting to make the entire run in one push. I made this decision mostly because I told the handlers that I was going to camp for three hours and I wasn’t sure if Jeri and Mike would be at the finish by the time I got there. A saying from the Teams came to mind, “Plan your dive, dive your plan.” With this in mind, I decided to “dive the plan.” I stopped the team, laid out straw and fed the puppers a gigantic meal. They all devoured their food (Gonzo ate an entire bag of meat snacks) before curling and catching a few z’s.
📸 by @wmphotographyakdogs

It got up to 50°F today. A little warm for the dogs but perfect for the little mushers. Spring is definitely on it’s way🐺🐶
.
#dadlife #feralboys #feralkids #daddydaycare
The dawg days of winter. ❄️🔱

THE FINAL CAMPOUT

After three hours of rest, Maverick and Bonnie led the team on the final stretch of the race. We traveled for about two hours before the trail led us off Birch Creek and across frozen lakes and muskegs. We eventually came to the ditch trail that parallels a road, an indicator that we only had a few more miles to go. I stopped the team and set the snow hook.  I walked down the line, stopping at each dog with a snack in hand, and told each of these incredible canines how great they did and how proud I was of them. When I got back to the sled, the dogs tilted their heads toward the sky, and in unison, began to howl. I stood on my runners and listened to their song, soaking in their delight. As their song faded, I looked ahead at the bright sun overhead. This was it. I popped the hook and the sled lurched forward. We were bound for the finish line…

THE FINAL MILE
 
A year ago my oldest son, Atlas, suffered a prolonged seizure which left him paralyzed. His recovery became our top priority but we were also just weeks away from welcoming our new baby, Max, into the world. We spent the rest of the winter trying to balance intensive therapies multiple times per week with caring for a newborn infant. This left late nights and early mornings to get all the chores around the house and kennel accomplished. Despite burning the candle at both ends, things began to fall apart. Although Atlas was slowly showing signs of recovery, my other responsibilities were not faring as well. We received an unusual amount of snow in a short period of time, causing my workshop roof to collapse, vehicles broke down, and our toyo stove (oil burning stove) needed to be repaired. To top it off, the snow accumulation turned a 6-foot fence into a 4-foot fence, allowing a dog to jump out of his pen and into a pen with a dog during her heat cycle which created a litter of puppies at the worst possible time for us.
 
It felt like everything I had worked so hard to create was imploding;  like the universe was trying to tell me it was time to give up dog mushing. It didn’t help that the previous winter, when there was only one kid in the picture, I was stay-at-home dad by day and dog musher by night. I was training for the Copper Basin 300 mile race. I would head out to train once Jeri got home from work at 8pm. Despite my best efforts, averaging only 3 hours of sleep most nights, I was unable to properly prepare my team for the race and we had to withdraw after 150 miles.
 
After 2 consecutive very difficult seasons, it was difficult to maintain hope for my future in dog mushing. Would it really be possible to make it to the finish line of a mid-distance race? Do I have the time, the energy, the drive to keep going?
 
After a lot of contemplation, late night talks with Jeri, and my natural predilection for stubbornness, I knew I had to try at least one more season. If for no other reason than to prove to my kid who was recovering from physical paralysis, that we don’t give up when the going gets tough...

Bonnie and Clyde leading the Pack.
Life is good, amigos.

A glimpse inside the @snowtrekker tent on a frosty night somewhere in Denali.

The daylight hours were spent traveling the endless wilderness with a team of Alaskan huskies, by nightfall we were cooking salmon fillets and elk steaks on top the wood stove. After feasting like kings of the bush, another log was thrown onto the fire before climbing into our sleeping bags for the night.
The last adventure of the mushing season…

Warmed by the comfort of a canvas wall tent and the companionship of loyal sled dogs…
.

Sometimes I can’t help but feel like I was born in the wrong era. I often find myself daydreaming about the simplicity and self-sufficiency of life before modern technology and conveniences took over. Despite the challenges and physical demands of my lifestyle, I feel a deep connection to the land and the traditions of my ancestors, and long for a simpler way of life that may be lost forever.
.

REFLECTIONS OF STRENGTH

One year ago, frozen frames captured a pivotal chapter in my life. In this photo, my youngest, snug in a chest harness, and my oldest, adventurous in a backpack, accompanied me on a daunting mission through our sled dog haven. Two buckets of water, two buckets of kibble, and a heart burdened with the weight of responsibility.

This season tested every fiber of my being—balancing the needs of my children and the tireless care of our magnificent pack. The challenges seemed insurmountable, but we persevered, driven by an unyielding love for both our pups and our little ones.

Today, as I gaze upon this snapshot, I can't help but rejoice. The passing of time has brought us growth and strength. My children, now older, lend their tiny hands to lighten the load. Together, we navigate this wild terrain, an unstoppable force forged by love and resilience. ❄️🔱

As the Iditarod sign-ups loom just a few weeks ahead and the dog mushing season readies itself to take flight in 3 short months, our minds are consumed with the 2023/2024 mushing season. @mrs_ftk and I have crafted a meticulous training plan, with a set of objectives that will guide us through the season, all with the grand ambition of conquering the formidable Iditarod.

For those unfamiliar with its mystique, the Iditarod is an awe-inspiring 1000-mile dog sled race, commencing outside of Anchorage and finishing triumphantly in Nome. This grueling contest demands the dedication of a team of 14 remarkable dogs. While we are allowed to drop a dog from the team if they fall ill, suffer an injury, or grow weary, we are strictly prohibited from adding new members to our pack.

At FTK, We have a total of 25 remarkable canines, a blend of active sled dogs and retired pets. However, when it comes to the Iditarod, we rely on a select group of 19 intrepid dogs. We take pride in being one of the smallest kennels to brave the Iditarod, leaving us with little margin for error. Thus, meticulous planning becomes our most invaluable ally and Jeri and I have tirelessly constructed our initial blueprint for the forthcoming season.

One of the most effective means of honing our dogs' skills for an arduous endeavor like the Iditarod is to embark on a series of mid-distance races leading up to the main event. These races provide our dogs with invaluable exposure to fellow canine athletes from around the globe, offering them a chance to encounter diverse bacteria and viruses they wouldn't typically encounter. By allowing our dogs to interact with other teams before Iditarod, we minimize the risk of them falling victim to an untimely bug along the trail. Our sights are set on several races leading up to the Iditarod this year, starting with the Solstice 100, followed by the Yukon Quest in February, and culminating in the ultimate test of endurance—the Iditarod in March. If fortune favors us and our dogs still possess the insatiable thirst for the run, we may even dare to take on the Kobuk 440 in April, contingent upon securing adequate funding and sponsorships.

This season brought challenges I never saw coming. Herniated disks left me sidelined, and my past career left me with cluster headaches, often referred to as suicide headaches. For months, I faced debilitating pain that affected every aspect of my life. I ended up in the emergency room on the brink of shock from the pain, my wife's unwavering support became my rock, but I couldn't shake the feeling of burdening those I love most. The darkness within grew, and I found myself contemplating an unimaginable path.

But sometimes, in our darkest hours, we find the strength to reach out for help, even when it feels impossible. 🤝

With the support of a dear friend, I connected with @themission_within, a retreat offering Ibogaine and DMT therapy. It was a leap of faith, and I used my Iditarod money to embark on this transformative journey. Little did I know, this experience would be a turning point in my life. 

I've been holding onto emotions for over 15 years, expressing them only through anger and frustration, a survival tactic ingrained in my time as a former team guy. But during this therapy, something incredible happened. The medicine guided me to release those bottled-up emotions, allowing a river of feelings to flow. As the weight lifted from my head, a newfound sense of lightness and relief emerged. 

This journey taught me a vital truth: denying ourselves the ability to feel can lead us down a dark and treacherous path. But when we choose to embrace our emotions and allow ourselves to heal, the power of transformation ignites within us. Psychedelics and the support of the amazing people I now call family became the lifelines that saved me from the brink.

Today, I stand here with gratitude overflowing in my heart. Grateful for the healing, the love, and the chance to cherish life's beauty once more. 🙏🏼

WE MUST FEEL TO HEAL.

Feels so much better to move my body out of love for myself instead of giving myself a brutal beat down…with endless shit talking.

I also need to take time and let my inner child come out more often and enjoy the simple things. One of the many lessons learned through the plant medicine. 🙏🏼🌌
Soaking up the love. ❤️ #fozziebear
I bee keeping’ it real from now on, friends. ❤️🐝🍯

Hey, everyone! I hope this message finds you well. Today, I wanted to open up and share some heartfelt reflections on the path ahead for FTK and myself.

Lately, life's been an exhilarating rollercoaster with so much on my plate—raising two wonderful kids, one of whom requires specialized care for cerebral palsy, while juggling multiple responsibilities, including maintaining our property and hosting an Airbnb.

Took my boys to the pond today where beavers taught us some truths. 

I explained to my kids that this pond didn’t exist until two beavers joined forces years ago. They chopped down trees and branches, tirelessly piling them in a small creek with mud and stones, gradually forming the pond. This sanctuary now shields the beavers from wolves and bears, providing them a secure haven to call home.

I shared with my boys that, much like those two beavers, it’s crucial to discover someone who truly believes in your vision to share your pond with. The world can be a harsh place, with bears and wolves lurking to take you down, but having a teammate or a ride-or-die, that will stand by you through thick or thin can make all the difference.

Maintain your focus on continuous progress rather than fixating solely on the end outcome. Imagine the daunting prospect if two beavers weighing 40-60 pounds each had encountered a small creek and fixated only on the labor required to form a pond. These beavers didn’t dwell on complaints like, “This is going to be an enormous task. It’ll take ages to complete.” They simply took the initiative and simply began.

And don’t forget, like these beavers still tending to their dam, our journey is always ongoing…

I then realized my kids weren’t even paying attention but I smiled bc these were lessons I needed to be reminded of. 🦫

I then told my kids, like the beavers…it’s important to take good care of your teeth.

#lessonsinnature

MUSHING SEASON OFFICIALLY STARTED!

The first runs of the season are focused around obedience and proper behavior on the line. We focus on what we call “The 3 No Chews”.

We teach the dogs that it’s not acceptable to chew on the lines, their harnesses, or each other.

Once we get that concept we head out for a short, little, fun run. Our first run was only 4 miles but we will slowly build from here…until we are able to run a 1000 mile race!

Fall is here! It’s officially TEAM DOG season!

@teamdog.pet 
@teamdog.shop

More signs of fall…

My main focus this year is training dogs, which means I won’t be spending two + weeks in the bush hunting. Instead, I’m hunting close to home on evenings and weekends. Time will tell if the universe deems me worthy of one of her bulls.

This has been the best start to training since the dawn of FTK. A big reason for that could be that there are no rookie dogs in the pack. Every dog running this season has at least one year running in harness. It’s almost like they’ve all done this before! Haha

Looking back several years ago…our very first runs at FTK were quite chaotic. Dogs chewed the lines, some fought, and others struggled to run in harness. We had a mixed team of dogs from retired mushers and the misfits that other mushers rejected. Some of the dogs didn’t understand the job and I, sure as shit, didn’t know what I was really doing either. 

But after a few years of failures and some successes…I began to learn more about dogs and how to properly train them.

Going into our 7th winter and mushing season, This has been the best start for us. Not only have the doggos shown a desire to run farther than I originally planned, but they've also been exceptionally well-behaved on the lines. There have been no incidents of line chewing (except for Buttercup once, but she hasn't repeated it since I gently corrected her by bitting her nose).

The dogs' behavior has made the start of this mushing season incredibly enjoyable. Because they've been so well-behaved, I've had the pleasure of bringing my kids along on many of these early season adventures.

So far we’re off to a great start and I can’t wait to keep this momentum rolling all the way to Nome! ❄️🔱

Six years ago, almost to the day, my wife, our dog Eleanor, and I embarked on this wild adventure.

We packed up everything, bid farewell to the familiar, and set our sights on Alaska, chasing the elusive dream of competing in the Iditarod with a team of dogs that we carefully bred, selected, and trained ourselves.

Over the past half-dozen years, our journey has been a rollercoaster ride through life's highs and lows, taking us up towering peaks and down into deep valleys. Amidst it all, we added two tiny adventurers to our crew – our kids, who have become an integral part of our Mushing lifestyle.

And today, my friends, marked a milestone we've been working towards. 

Drumroll, please!…
…We officially signed up for @theiditarod . It's a pinch-me moment; surreal doesn't even begin to describe it. We're now one giant leap closer to turning our audacious dream into a reality!

Thank you to all of you who have supported us on this journey. We couldn’t have made it to this point without you. 

Much Love!

❄️🔱
These early season runs always seem to  be the coldest for me. It’s hard to stay warm on the ATV and wet snow turns me into a bitch.

Three months ago, I went to a psychedelic retreat in Mexico, experiencing Ibogaine and Five MEO DMT. It was a life-changing even. Since then, I've bid farewell to my vices. Cannabis, caffeine, and alcohol were all left behind.

Recently, I've cautiously reintroduced them into my life, but with purpose. Cannabis now enhances my meditation, allowing me to go deeper.  Caffeine is reserved for moments when I truly need that extra boost (and I still stay away from booze). 

The other night, faced with a never ending to-do list and the need to exercise my dogs late into the night, I turned to a cup of coffee.

What followed was pretty crazy. Fatigue and sluggishness were replaced by an overwhelming surge of energy, igniting my excitement to take my dogs on a run through the darkness. It was a vivid reminder that moderation is key, and that even caffeine, when used intentionally, can be one hell of a drug.

I want to share an experience I had over the weekend. Mostly because I'm convinced that the world could greatly benefit from embracing plant medicines, particularly among those in positions of authority. It's my strong belief that psychedelics, unfairly stigmatized in the past, hold the potential to offer profound insights and facilitate the healing of deep rooted traumas.

Over the weekend, I embarked on a journey with a high dose of psilocybin 🍄. My intention was to gain insights on how to best lead my dogs through the upcoming winter and to explore my inner subconscious mind.

As the mushrooms began their work, I was shown that @mrs_ftk and my souls were bound together before we entered this world, destined to be. It showed me thats how we endured years of a long-distance relationship and overcame countless trials since we first met as 12 year olds at our community pool.

My thoughts then drifted to the Middle East and Ukraine, feeling heartbreak for innocent lives affected by war. My anger and grief transformed into profound love for fellow humans. I imagined a world where leaders resolved conflicts through unity and empathy. I thought of how great the world would be if its leaders would sit together and take entheogenic compounds and learn to love all humanity.

Returning to my intention, I contemplated how to support my dogs, particularly for the Iditarod. The mushrooms advised me to lead with love, lighting the way with my heart, and if I lose my way to lead with my gut, trusting my intuition when in doubt.

This was my first experience with a high dose of 🍄, different from my expectations but exactly what I needed. The mushrooms told me to return before the Yukon Quest 300. I intend to heed their guidance. 🍄❤️
There is no better way to travel through the winter woods.

A myriad of obstacles can impede a dog team’s journey to Nome, striking during training or the race, even when everything seems flawlessly executed by the musher.

Recently, on a frigid night, 20 miles into a training run, Animal’s demeanor shifted abruptly. He ceased pulling, and as I halted the team, he succumbed to a brief seizure. After ensuring his comfort in the sled bag, we Continued mission and resumed our course.

Navigating a fork in the trail, the decision weighed heavy; a right turn meant an additional 20 training miles (my original plan), while a left offered a quick route home in under 5 miles. Opting for the latter, we ventured forth.

After approximately 10 minutes, a déjà vu unfolded as Piggy mirrored Animal’s pre-seizure behavior, eventually succumbing to a longer seizure. Armed with Diazepam, I prepared for intervention, yet her seizure subsided. With a brief recovery period, Piggy joined Animal in the sled as we journeyed back home.

The relief? Piggy and Animal emerged unscathed. The seizures likely stemmed from the exertion of running, a phenomenon unprecedented for them. The somber news? They bid farewell to the Iditarod team, a significant blow for our small kennel, lacking replacements for these dedicated companions. 

Now, with a diminished team of 17, a strategic shift awaits. We’ll consolidate into one unit, fostering enhanced training and consecutive miles for the entire FTK Wolf Pack.

In the face of adversity, I heed the lesson to embrace the universe’s hand, recognizing that within challenges lies a silver lining. So, mush on, amigos, through all the twists that fate lays in our paths.
Despite feeling sick it was a good day. Thanks @mrs_ftk for giving me a push when I need it and reeling me back when I’m going too hard.
